  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds appear legitimate by disguising their true origin. This activity undermines the integrity of financial systems and facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, and terrorism financing.\n\nIn China, the legal framework to combat money laundering is robust. The Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China, along with other relevant regulations, establishes stringent measures to prevent and combat money laundering activities. Financial institutions and certain non-financial entities are required to implement comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) programs, including customer due diligence, suspicious transaction reporting, and record-keeping. Violations of these laws can result in severe penalties, including fines, imprisonment, and other legal consequences.\n\nThe Chinese government is committed to maintaining financial order and national security by rigorously enforcing anti-money laundering laws and cooperating with international efforts to combat this illicit activity.",
